Appendix A_Statutory and Regulatory Framework of the Trading Practices Rules 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
This appendix provides a background summary of the antifraud and antimanipulation provisions of the Securities
Exchange Act of 1934 (``Exchange Act''),
<FOOTCITE>1</FOOTCITE>
 the promulgation of Rules 10b&hyph;6, 10b&hyph;7, and 10b&hyph;8 (``Trading Practices Rules'') under their authority,
and an index of the relevant interpretive and rulemaking releases subsequent to the rules' adoption in 1955. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<FOOTNOTE>
<FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->
1
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

</FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->
15 U.S.C. 78a et seq. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
</FOOTNOTE>

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=73 g=1 f=1 -->
I. Background
<FOOTCITE>2</FOOTCITE>

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<FOOTNOTE>
<FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

</FOOTNAME>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->
See generally III L. Loss, Securities Regulation 1541&hyph;1570 (2d. ed. 1961); Foshay, Market Activities of Participants
in Securities Distributions, 45 U. Va. L. Rev. 907, 907&hyph;926 (1959). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
</FOOTNOTE>

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
Following the 1929 stock market crash and amid public furor concerning financial intermediaries that had engaged
in flagrant manipulation in the securities markets, Congress enacted the Exchange Act to put an end to the practices
that it found had contributed to the economic problems facing the Nation.
<FOOTCITE>3</FOOTCITE>
 In drafting the legislation, Congress determined that the available common law remedies for fraud were inadequate
to combat manipulation in the securities markets.
<FOOTCITE>4</FOOTCITE>
 Because Congress recognized that market manipulation can assume many forms, it did not define the term in the Exchange
Act or elsewhere. Congress intended the Exchange Act to outlaw every ``device used to persuade the public that activity
in a security is the reflection of a genuine demand instead of a mirage.''
<FOOTCITE>5</FOOTCITE>
 In a number of provisions, the Commission is given authority to define manipulative practices and adopt rules to proscribe
and prevent such conduct.
<FOOTCITE>6</FOOTCITE>
 As the Commission has stated: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<FOOTNOTE>
<FOOTNAME>
