<SUMMARY>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=10 g=1 f=2 -->
SUMMARY:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=10 g=1 f=1 -->
 ATF is proposing to amend trade practice regulations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under the Federal Alcohol Administration (FAA) Act on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
tied-house, exclusive outlets, commercial bribery, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
consignment sales by adding standards for enforcing the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``exclusion'' element where appropriate and by revising other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulations as the result of an agency review and an industry 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
petition. Under the FAA Act, ``exclusion, in whole or in part, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of distilled spirits, wine, or malt beverages, sold or offered 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for sale by other persons'' is a necessary element of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
violation of the tied-house, exclusive outlets or commercial 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
bribery provisions. Recent court rulings have raised questions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
concerning ATF's traditional interpretation of the term 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
``exclusion''. ATF intends to use rulemaking to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) promulgate a framework for establishing ``exclusion,'' (2) identify promotional practices which result in
retailer 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
control, (3) identify promotional practices which result in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exclusion under the Act, and (4) identify those practices for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
which there is no likelihood that exclusion will result and for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
which the Bureau will not take action (safe harbors). Other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regulatory amendments are also made as a result of an ATF 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
review of the regulations and an industry petition submitted in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1992.
