SUPPLEMENTARY INFORMATION:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Federal Alcohol Administration Act 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Federal Alcohol Administration Act (hereinafter 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
referred to as FAA Act or Act) provides for Federal regulation of the alcoholic beverage industry. The FAA Act contains

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
particular restrictions that are unique to the alcoholic 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
beverage industry and reflects Congress' concern with a variety 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of trade practices and abuses that took place before, during 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and immediately after Prohibition. This notice of proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rulemaking focuses on four parts of the statute, Exclusive 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Outlet (27 U.S.C. 205(a)), Tied-House (27 U.S.C. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
205(b)), Commercial Bribery (27 U.S.C. 205(c)), and Consignment 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Sales (27 U.S.C. 205(d)). The supplementary information is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
divided into two sections. The first section deals with the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
subject of exclusion, and the second section covers other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
changes proposed as a result of an internal review of trade 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
practice regulations and an industry petition.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Exclusion 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
One element which is necessary for these practices to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
result in violation of Federal law is ``exclusion, in whole or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in part, of distilled spirits, wine, or malt beverages, sold or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
offered for sale by other persons.'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Although exclusion is not defined in the FAA Act or in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
current implementing regulations at 27 CFR parts 6, 8 and 10, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF has, in the past, held that ``exclusion in part'' includes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
causing retailers to purchase less of a competing brand than 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
they otherwise would have bought. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In a recent decision, however, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Fedway Associates, Inc., et 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
al. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
v. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
United States Treasury, Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (Fedway),
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 976 F.2d 1416 (DC Cir. 1992) the United 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
held that Congress had intended something more than just a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
retailer purchasing less of a competing brand than it otherwise 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
would have and for a violation to occur there must also be a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
tie or link between a supplier and retailer that at least 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
threatens the retailer's independence. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The court based this conclusion on several points. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
court said ``exclusion'' means to exclude a rival product from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the marketplace by some direct action of the violator. Merely 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
taking some action which influences a retailer not to purchase 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a rival product is not exclusion under the Act if the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
retailer's response is the result of a free economic choice. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
This interpretation of exclusion as meaning the shutting out or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
expelling of a rival's product, according to the court, is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
consistent with conduct addressed by the Act such as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
tied-house, commercial bribery and exclusive outlets. Any 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
broader interpretation would, in the view of the court, likely 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
result in restriction of pro-competitive activities. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->
