<DOCNO> FR940426-1-00045 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940426-1-00006 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Meaning of Terms Revisions in Parts 6, 8, 10 and 11 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
ATF is proposing to add the terms ``ATF officer'' and ``Director'' to the definitions in 27 CFR 6.11, 8.11, 10.11, and
11.11 to correspond to the terms in the proposed administrative provisions in &sect;&sect;6.5, 8.5, 10.5, and 11.5,
discussed above. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF is proposing to define the term ``brand'' in 27 CFR 6.11, since a number of dollar limitations on things of value
which may lawfully be given to retailers is on a ``per brand'' basis. The definition proposed is drawn from ATF Ruling
81&hyph;1, Q.B. 1981&hyph;2, page 27, but ATF has narrowed the proposed definition to exclude changes in the color
or design of the label. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF is proposing adding the term ``Regional director (compliance)'' to the definitions in 27 CFR 6.11, 8.11 and 10.11
to correspond to the term in the proposed administrative provisions. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The petitioners believe that the definition of ``retailer'' should be revised in 27 CFR parts 6 and 8. The current provision
excludes wholesalers who make incidental retail sales representing less than 5 percent of their sales during the
preceding two months. The petitioners state that a supplier cannot know whether the wholesaler's retail sales are
within the 5 percent limitation and suggest eliminating that standard. The petitioners also believe that the definition
of ``retailer'' should be clarified in order to ensure that this definition is consistent with &sect;6.2 which defines
the territorial extent of part 6 of the regulations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF believes that removal of the 5 percent limitation would make the definition too broad. For example, without the
percent limitations, a wholesaler who makes a single sale to a consumer is deemed to be a retailer. Also, the petitioners'
proposed definition would exclude, as a retailer, someone within the United States who makes sales for consumption
outside of the United States; i.e., a duty free shop. The FAA Act itself does not allow this type of exception to the territorial
coverage of the law. Therefore, ATF does not agree with this proposal. For the same reasons, ATF does not agree with
the proposed amendment to the definition of ``retailer establishment.'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF is proposing to change the term ``retailer establishment'' in 27 CFR 6.11 to ``retail establishment'', since
that is the term used in 27 CFR part 6 regulations. The term ``retail establishment'' in 27 CFR 8.11 will be removed because
the term is not used in 27 CFR part 8 regulations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Part 6_``Tied-House'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Sections 6.25 Through 6.33, Interest in Retail Licensee 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The petitioners state that these sections of the regulations provide identical treatment concerning an interest
of an industry member in a license with respect to a retailer's premises (&sect;&sect;6.25&hyph;6.27) and in real
or personal property owned, occupied, or used by the retailer in the conduct of the business (&sect;&sect;6.31&hyph;6.33).
The petitioners feel that combining the provisions, which they believe parallel each other (&sect;&sect;6.25 and
6.31; 6.26 and 6.32; and 6.27 and 6.33), will enhance the simplicity and clarity of the rules. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Further, the petitioners recommend clarifying changes to existing regulations to ensure that there is no misunderstanding
that a violation of the FAA Act does not occur merely upon a finding of the existence of the means to induce. The petitioners
believe that the wording of several existing regulations describing various means to induce results in industry
confusion since such sections are written in terms describing ``prohibited means to induce.'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The petitioners believe that the term ``prohibited'' should be deleted from such sections in order to avoid any contention
or confusion that this provision, read separately from &sect;6.21, allows for finding a violation of the FAA Act without
also establishing that the means to induce results in exclusion. While the petitioners recognize that these sections
are subject to the general application provisions of &sect;6.21, which states that these means to induce are unlawful
only if they result in exclusion, they believe such a change will help reduce the possibility of industry confusion
on this issue. The same request was made concerning &sect;&sect;6.31, 6.41, 6.51, 6.61, 6.65 and 6.71, which all contain
similar language. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF does not object to revising the language in &sect;&sect;6.25, 6.31, 6.41, 6.51, 6.61, 6.65 and 6.71. ATF proposes
to adopt this suggestion but would replace the word ``inducement,'' with ``means to induce,'' in order to correspond
with the wording of the FAA Act. Conforming changes were also made to the language in &sect;&sect;6.27 and 6.33. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF does not believe that the provisions of &sect;&sect;6.25 through 6.33 should be combined in the various ways proposed
by the petitioners. From a structural point of view, merging &sect;&sect;6.25 through 6.33 fundamentally alters
the organization of subpart C of part 6. Subpart C is divided into topics (with titles) which parallel sections 105(b)(1)
through (7) of the FAA Act. The proposed merger of the corresponding sections will mean that the regulations applicable
to an interest in retail property under section 105(b)(2) will be contained in a group of the regulations categorized
under an interest in a retail license under section 105(b)(1). ATF believes that it may be confusing for a person or
industry representative relying on the part 6 regulations to look under the regulations on a retail license for a regulation
relating to an interest in retail property. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940426-1-00046 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940426-1-00006 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.42, Third Party Arrangements 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
ATF's review of its regulations disclosed that some confusion exists over the breadth of the proscription on indirect
means to induce. Some industry members incorrectly view the two examples in &sect;6.42 as exclusive of the situations
covered by the regulation. Additionally, ATF believes some industry members interpret the examples as meaning the
third party receiving the means to induce must be an agent of an individual retailer. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
By enacting the phrase ``directly or indirectly or through an affiliate,'' Congress intended the broadest possible
application of the proscriptions of the FAA Act. The term ``indirectly'' encompasses more than simply trade practice
activities with agents of retailers. It covers such activities with any representative of a retailer or industry
member, whether or not such representative is technically an agent of the retailer or industry member. Thus, an industry
member providing the means to induce to any third party who will pass the means on to the retailer, or use them in a manner
to benefit the retailer, is indirectly providing the means to induce to the retailer. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Accordingly, ATF proposes revising &sect;6.42 to clarify that the examples are simply illustrative and not exclusive
of the situations resulting in indirect 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
inducements. A revision to the final sentence is proposed for clarity. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.43, Sale of Equipment 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The petitioners recommend deleting the last sentence of &sect;6.43. The petitioners believe that negotiation by
an industry member with an equipment company for a special price for a retailer for equipment should not be a means to
induce unless the industry member subsidizes the special price. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF does not agree. The means to induce is not the special price, but the service provided by the industry member in negotiating
with the equipment company, or using its influence on behalf of the retailer. In the past, ATF has experienced cases
in which a retailer, believing that it received special price consideration, altered its buying patterns resulting
in exclusion of a competitor's products. Also, a conforming change to the cross-reference is proposed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.46, Outside Signs 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
ATF proposes to make outside signs an exception in subpart D. See the discussion under proposed &sect;6.102. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.47, Items Intended for Consumers 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The petitioners recommend deleting this section because they believe that it is redundant and unnecessary in light
of &sect;6.93 and their proposed revisions to &sect;6.87. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ATF proposes to remove this section since the general prohibition in &sect;6.41 covers things of value not specifically
excepted in subpart D. Those of the examples listed in &sect;6.47 which ATF proposes to allow will be listed in the proposed
revision of &sect;6.84, Point of sale advertising and consumer advertising specialties. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.52, Cooperative Advertising 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
ATF proposes that the phrase ``placed by the retailer'' be deleted from this section and that language be added to emphasize
that it does not matter whether the retailer or the industry member places the advertisement. The means to induce to
be addressed here is the cooperative nature of the transaction and the benefit received by the retailer. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
For clarity, ATF proposes cross-referencing &sect;6.52 to &sect;6.98, Advertising Service. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.67, Sales to a Retailer Whose Account is in Arrears 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
ATF's current position is contained in Revenue Ruling 54&hyph;162, 1954&hyph;1 C.B. 340. On August 1, 1979, ATF proposed
a regulation (Notice No. 327, 44 FR 45298) on credit arrears which would have provided that a supplier could continue
to sell to a retailer, with unpaid purchases existing in excess of 30 days, without violating the extension of credit
provision if the retailer either made payments in accordance with Revenue Ruling 54&hyph;162 or the amount of arrears
did not exceed an average purchase by the retailer from the supplier over the preceding 4 month period. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Commenters on the proposal objected to the proposal stating that it would require extensive bookkeeping checks or
it might force repayment of large outstanding debts in order to keep dealing with a wholesaler. Several commenters
recommended that ATF simply adhere to the credit requirements imposed by State law. ATF withdrew the proposal (T.D.
ATF&hyph;74, 45 FR 63242, September 23, 1980) from further consideration. ATF is again raising the issue and proposing
to adopt in the regulations the position stated in Revenue Ruling 54&hyph;162. However, comments on other possible
approaches will be considered. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.71, Quota Sales and Section 6.72, Tie-in Sales 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
In addition to the language change to &sect;6.71 discussed under &sect;6.41, the petitioners propose to eliminate
the tie-in prohibition in &sect;6.72 and consolidate the remaining provisions into &sect;6.71. The petitioners
recommend deleting the first two sentences of &sect;6.72 because they believe that there is no statutory basis for
this regulation under the FAA Act. The petitioners state that the classic ``tying relationship'' prohibited by the
antitrust laws is not addressed by section 105 of the FAA Act notwithstanding that subsection 105(b) of the FAA Act
bears the heading ``Tied-House.'' The petitioners further state that prohibitions against tie-in agreements are
covered adequately by the Federal antitrust laws. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940426-1-00047 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940426-1-00006 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The tie-in sale described in the regulations is a form of quota sale covered by the Act. Moreover, ATF feels that &sect;6.71
and &sect;6.72 are distinct from one another and should be kept separate to insure clarity and foster understanding
of the regulations. The fact that another Federal law may apply to such a practice is not relevant to whether such a practice
is covered by the FAA Act. Additionally, ATF proposes revising &sect;6.72 to cover expressly a particular type of
transaction as a tie-in sale. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Subpart D_Exceptions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Many changes discussed in the first section of the Supplementary Information on Exclusion affect this subpart. The
discussion which follows is limited to specific requests by the industry or findings of ATF's own internal review
which were not discussed in that earlier section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.81, General 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The petitioners propose amending &sect;6.81(a) by deleting the second sentence which prohibits an industry member
from conditioning the providing of items or services allowed under subpart D on the purchase of distilled spirits,
wine, or malt beverages. ATF agrees this prohibition is not necessary for most items, and will remove the prohibition
from the general section and place it in the specific sections where such conditioning has been a concern, for instance,
&sect;6.83 on product displays. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section 6.81(b), Recordkeeping requirements, requires industry members to maintain certain records which can
be used to substantiate claims that items provided to retailers are within the subpart D exceptions to the tied-house
prohibitions. The petitioners propose deleting &sect;6.81(b) in its entirety, thereby eliminating all recordkeeping
requirements. The petitioners state that ``(t)his change should be adopted because the FAA Act neither provides
nor suggests that any such requirements can be imposed.'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The petitioners further state that if it is decided not to delete &sect;6.81(b) in its entirety, they recommend the
addition of language to this paragraph to make it clear that no separate violation of the FAA Act shall arise from the
failure of an industry member to maintain records in accordance with the requirements of &sect;6.81(b). The petitioners
believe that the FAA Act neither creates nor supports the existence of any such violation of the FAA Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The proposal to eliminate the requirement to keep records which substantiate industry members' claims that items
provided retailers are within the exceptions would negate ATF's capability to verify compliance with the dollar
limitations and any other requirements of subpart D. The limitations in each exception section of the regulations
would be unenforceable if ATF had no way to verify compliance with the requirements of such exceptions. Where the industry
member fails to keep the required records, the industry member is not eligible for the regulatory exception in that
particular transaction. No separate recordkeeping violation would be charged. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.82, Cost Adjustment Factor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
While the petitioners do not request a specific change to this section, they request that ATF explore alternate methods
which would be cost effective for ATF to convey this information in a manner that continues to ensure that all permittees
are apprised of the annual dollar adjustments. Instead, ATF proposes to delete this section and periodically review
the amounts if necessary. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
Section 6.83, Product Displays 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The petitioners recommended amending the definition of product display to substitute ``*&blank;*&blank;* and
similar items the primary function of which is to hold, display or shelve consumer products.'' for ``*&blank;*&blank;*
and the like,'' which appears in the current regulation. ATF is incorporating this change in its proposed revision,
but proposes the phrase ``hold and display'' for clarity. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The petitioners also requested that ATF amend the dollar limitation in the regulation to reflect the current adjusted
rate. Instead, ATF proposes a $500 per brand at any one time per retail establishment limitation for the current limitation
of $100 (as adjusted) per year per brand per retail establishment. As noted earlier, ATF proposes narrowing the definition
of the term ``brand'' and requests comments on the definition. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

